NEW_DATA = {
"31": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 31 is the theological heart of the Book of Consolation (chapters 30–33) and one of the most theologically dense chapters in the entire Hebrew Bible. <strong>At that time, declares YHWH, I will be the God of all the clans of Israel, and they shall be my people</strong>. The covenant formula (<em>I will be their God; they shall be my people</em>) expands here beyond the traditional scope — <em>all the clans of Israel</em> encompasses the reunification of both the northern and southern kingdoms. The northern tribes deported by Assyria in 722 BC had been effectively lost; this promise of restoration includes them.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH: The people who survived the sword found grace in the wilderness; when Israel sought for rest, YHWH appeared to him from far away</strong>. The wilderness-grace motif evokes the Exodus: Israel found grace (<em>chen</em>) in the wilderness of Sinai after surviving Egypt's sword. The new-Exodus structure of the restoration anticipates a parallel experience: the survivors of the Babylonian exile will find the same grace in the wilderness of their journey home that their ancestors found after Egypt. YHWH appearing from far away is the divine initiative of restoration — he comes toward the exiles, not waiting for them to return on their own.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>I have loved you with an everlasting love; therefore I have continued my faithfulness to you</strong>. <em>Ahavat olam</em> (everlasting love) — the divine love for Israel is not contingent on Israel's performance or limited to a period of good behavior. It precedes the covenant, persists through covenant violation, and will outlast the exile. <em>Therefore I have continued my faithfulness</em> (<em>al-ken meshachtika chesed</em>, I have drawn you with covenant-love): the everlasting love is the ground of the <em>chesed</em> (covenant faithfulness/steadfast love) that enables restoration. This verse is one of the most explicit statements of divine unconditional love in the Hebrew Bible.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>Again I will build you, and you shall be built, O virgin Israel! Again you shall adorn yourself with tambourines and shall go forth in the dance of the merrymakers</strong>. The <em>virgin Israel</em> image (cf. 18:13) is restored: the nation that was violated and shamed in exile is addressed as virgin — not because the past is erased but because YHWH's restoration gives a new beginning. The tambourines and dancing recall Miriam's victory celebration at the sea (Exod 15:20–21): the new Exodus will produce the same community celebration as the first.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>Again you shall plant vineyards on the mountains of Samaria; the planters shall plant and shall enjoy the fruit</strong>. The mountains of Samaria — the northern kingdom's heartland — will be restored to agriculture. This is a specific promise to the northern tribes: the land from which they were deported will be theirs again. <em>Shall enjoy the fruit</em>: the covenant blessing of Deuteronomy 28:30 (you plant but shall not enjoy) is reversed. The curse of frustrated labor is lifted; the planter will eat the harvest.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>For there shall be a day when watchmen will call in the hill country of Ephraim: Arise, and let us go up to Zion, to YHWH our God</strong>. Watchmen on Ephraim's hills (<em>Shomron</em>, the northern kingdom's territory) calling people to go up to Zion for worship — the reunification image in its simplest form. The northern kingdom that had been worshiping at Bethel and Dan under Jeroboam's golden calves (1 Kgs 12:28–30) will once again go to Jerusalem to worship YHWH. The division of the kingdom and its alternative worship centers will be healed.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>For thus says YHWH: Sing aloud with gladness for Jacob, and raise shouts for the chief of the nations; proclaim, give praise, and say, O YHWH, save your people, the remnant of Israel</strong>. The call to celebratory shout (<em>rinnah</em>) and save-cry (<em>yoshia YHWH et-amkha</em>) frames the restoration as a salvation-event requiring both joyful proclamation and urgent prayer. <em>Chief of the nations</em> (<em>rosh haggoyim</em>): Israel's covenant standing as YHWH's treasured people (Deut 7:6) is restored. The <em>remnant</em> (<em>she'erit</em>) — those who survived judgment — are the focus of YHWH's saving attention.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>Behold, I will bring them from the north country and gather them from the farthest parts of the earth, among them the blind and the lame, the pregnant woman and she who is in labor, together; a great company, they shall return here</strong>. The ingathering from the north country (Babylon) and the far ends of the earth encompasses the full diaspora. The inclusion of the most vulnerable — blind, lame, pregnant, laboring — signals that the restoration is not reserved for the strong and capable. In contrast to ancient military deportations that typically drove populations mercilessly, YHWH's regathering includes those who would be left behind in any human operation.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>With weeping they shall come, and with pleas for mercy I will lead them back, I will make them walk by brooks of water, in a straight path in which they shall not stumble; for I am a father to Israel, and Ephraim is my firstborn</strong>. <em>With weeping and pleas for mercy</em> (<em>bivchi uvetachanun</em>): the return is not triumphant but penitent — the exiles come back acknowledging the reason for the exile. <em>Brooks of water, straight path</em>: the new-Exodus through a well-watered desert contrasts with the wilderness wandering of the first Exodus (Isa 40:3–4; 43:19–20). <em>Father to Israel, Ephraim my firstborn</em>: the divine fatherhood established at the Exodus (Exod 4:22 — Israel is my firstborn son) is here extended specifically to Ephraim, the northern kingdom's primary tribe. YHWH's paternal love for the lost northern tribes is as real as for Judah.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>Hear the word of YHWH, O nations, and declare it in the coastlands far away; say, He who scattered Israel will gather him, and will keep him as a shepherd keeps his flock</strong>. The nations are summoned as witnesses and heralds: the God who scattered Israel will gather him. The shepherd-king image (cf. 23:3–4 — YHWH as shepherd of the restored flock) frames the ingathering as pastoral care rather than political conquest. The news of YHWH's regathering is to be proclaimed in the coastlands — the most distant territories — as a testimony to YHWH's universal sovereignty.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>For YHWH has ransomed Jacob and has redeemed him from hands too strong for him</strong>. <em>Ransomed</em> (<em>padah</em>) and <em>redeemed</em> (<em>ga'al</em>) — two covenantal rescue terms. <em>Padah</em> is used of the Exodus redemption (Deut 7:8; 9:26; 13:5) and ransoming firstborn sons (Exod 13:13). <em>Ga'al</em> is the kinsman-redeemer language of Ruth — the one who has the right and responsibility to restore lost family members to their inheritance. Applied to YHWH's rescue of Israel from Babylon, the two terms claim that the restoration is both an act of sovereign redemption and an act of covenantal family obligation.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>They shall come and sing aloud on the height of Zion, and they shall be radiant over the goodness of YHWH, over the grain, the wine, and the oil, and over the young of the flock and the herd; their life shall be like a watered garden, and they shall languish no more</strong>. The covenant blessings of Deuteronomy 28:3–8 are listed: grain, wine, oil, flocks, herds — the fullness of agricultural prosperity. <em>Radiant over the goodness of YHWH</em> (<em>venaharu el-tuv YHWH</em>): the restored people shine with the reflected goodness they receive. <em>Like a watered garden</em>: the desert-scrub image from 17:6 (the person who trusts in flesh) is reversed — the covenant community becomes a lush, well-irrigated garden.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>Then shall the young women rejoice in the dance, and the young men and the old shall be glad. I will turn their mourning into joy; I will comfort them, and give them gladness for sorrow</strong>. The complete social spectrum — young women, young men, old people — will rejoice together. The transformation of mourning into joy (<em>vehafekhti eblam lesas</em>) is a reversal of the covenant curse of chapter 16 (no mourning, no celebration — both silenced). The restoration of joy is not merely personal but communal, generational, and holistic. NT resonance: the divine comforting of those who mourn (Matt 5:4; Rev 21:4 — he will wipe away every tear).</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>I will feast the soul of the priests with abundance, and my people shall be satisfied with my goodness, declares YHWH</strong>. The priests — who receive their portion from the offerings brought to the Temple — will be abundantly provided for in the restoration. <em>Saturate the soul of the priests</em> (<em>verivveti nefesh hakohanim deshen</em>): the priestly system of covenant worship will function properly, with the Temple service restored and the priests receiving their designated portions. <em>My people shall be satisfied with my goodness</em>: the comprehensive satisfaction of covenant blessing — material, spiritual, and relational.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH: A voice is heard in Ramah, lamentation and bitter weeping. Rachel is weeping for her children; she refuses to be comforted for her children, because they are no more</strong>. One of the most powerful poetic images in the prophets. Rachel, the beloved wife of Jacob who died in childbirth (Gen 35:19), weeps for her children — the Israelite tribes descended from her sons Joseph and Benjamin — who are going into exile past Ramah, the deportation staging point north of Jerusalem (40:1). The matriarch's inconsolable grief captures the depth of national loss. Matthew 2:18 applies this verse to the massacre of the Bethlehem infants — in both cases, Rachel weeps for children taken before their time.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH: Keep your voice from weeping, and your eyes from tears, for there is a reward for your work, declares YHWH, and they shall come back from the land of the enemy</strong>. YHWH answers Rachel's weeping with comfort: <em>keep your voice from weeping</em> (<em>minei qolech mibechi</em>). The exile will end; the children will return. <em>A reward for your work</em> (<em>yeish sachar liphe'ulatekh</em>): Rachel's faithfulness — her love and grief for her children — will be rewarded with their return. The covenant parent-child relationship is not severed by exile but strained, and the strain will be resolved in restoration.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>There is hope for your future, declares YHWH, and your children shall come back to their own country</strong>. <em>There is hope for your future</em> (<em>yeish-tikvah le'acharitekh</em>): the future hope that was stated in 29:11 (<em>a future and a hope</em>) is here directed at Rachel — the grieving matriarch represents all the bereaved parents of the exile. The children will return; the exile does not define the endpoint.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>I have heard Ephraim grieving, You have disciplined me, and I was disciplined, like an untrained calf; bring me back that I may be restored, for you are YHWH my God</strong>. Ephraim (the northern kingdom, personified) speaks repentance. The <em>untrained calf</em> (<em>egel lo-lummad</em>) image is that of a young bovine that resists the yoke before being broken to it — exactly the stiff-necked resistance to YHWH's covenant that produced the exile. Ephraim's prayer — <em>bring me back that I may be restored</em> (<em>hashiveni ve'ashuv</em>) — is the classic return-formula of the prophets (cf. Lam 5:21). The acknowledgment that YHWH is God (<em>attah YHWH Elohai</em>) is the beginning of covenant restoration.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>For after I had turned away, I relented, and after I was instructed, I struck my thigh; I was ashamed, and I was confounded, because I bore the disgrace of my youth</strong>. Ephraim's repentance continues: <em>struck my thigh</em> (<em>sapaqti al-yarech</em>) — a gesture of shock, shame, or remorse (cf. Ezek 21:12). The <em>disgrace of my youth</em> (<em>cherpat ne'urai</em>) is the apostasy of the early monarchy period — the golden calves of Jeroboam, the Baal worship that characterized the northern kingdom from its inception. Ephraim is not merely lamenting recent exile but acknowledging the deep ancestral rebellion that produced it.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>Is Ephraim my dear son? Is he my darling child? For as often as I speak against him, I do remember him still. Therefore my heart yearns for him; I will surely have mercy on him, declares YHWH</strong>. YHWH's response to Ephraim's repentance is one of the most moving expressions of divine parental love in Scripture. <em>Dear son, darling child</em> (<em>ben yaqir, yeled sha'ashu'im</em>): YHWH speaks of Ephraim with tenderness. <em>My heart yearns for him</em> (<em>hameh me'ai lo</em>): the Hebrew literally describes YHWH's intestines/womb (<em>me'im</em>) churning with compassion — the same physical-emotional imagery used for a mother's compassion (1 Kgs 3:26). <em>I will surely have mercy on him</em>: the doubled verbal form (<em>rachem arachamennu</em>) expresses the certainty and intensity of divine compassion. This verse is one of the most important contributions to the theology of divine pathos in the Hebrew Bible.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>Set up road markers for yourself; make yourself guideposts; consider well the highway, the road by which you went. Return, O virgin Israel, return to these your cities</strong>. The road markers and guideposts on the highway from Babylon back to Israel: the returning exiles need navigational aids for the journey home. The practical instruction is also metaphorical: the path of the new Exodus must be consciously prepared and followed. <em>Return, O virgin Israel</em>: the address uses the same restored-virgin image as v4 — the exile does not permanently desecrate the national identity but creates the conditions for restored covenant relationship.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>How long will you waver, O faithless daughter? For YHWH has created a new thing on the earth: a woman encircles a man</strong>. The enigmatic final clause — <em>a woman encircles a man</em> (<em>neqevah tesovev gaver</em>) — is one of the most debated verses in Jeremiah. Interpretations range from: (1) a role-reversal image where Israel (the woman) takes initiative in pursuing YHWH (the man); (2) a fertility restoration image (a woman will again be able to carry a man-child); (3) a new-creation inversion where familiar categories are transformed. The <em>new thing YHWH creates</em> is unprecedented — it falls outside existing categories. Whatever the specific referent, the verse signals that the restoration will involve a genuinely new act of divine creation, not merely a return to the status quo ante.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH of hosts, the God of Israel: Once more they shall use these words in the land of Judah and in its cities, when I restore their fortunes: YHWH bless you, O habitation of righteousness, O holy hill!</strong> The blessing formula that will once again be pronounced in restored Judah — <em>YHWH bless you, O habitation of righteousness</em> — is a covenantal greeting that presupposes the presence of righteousness in the place. Restored Jerusalem will deserve and receive the blessing vocabulary that exilic Jerusalem had forfeited. The <em>holy hill</em> is Zion, restored to its covenantal function as the place of divine presence and covenant administration.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>And Judah and all its cities shall dwell there together, and the farmers and those who wander with their flocks</strong>. The restored land will support the full range of Judahite economic life: settled farmers and nomadic shepherds coexisting in the same territory. This represents a comprehensive social restoration — not just the return of urban population but the full agricultural and pastoral community that made up the covenant society. The land itself is recovered as the sustaining environment for covenant life.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>For I will satisfy the weary soul, and every languishing soul I will replenish</strong>. The divine promise of comprehensive renewal: <em>the weary soul</em> (<em>nefesh ayefah</em>) and <em>languishing soul</em> (<em>nefesh da'avah</em>) describe the exhausted, depleted exiles — those worn out by the long journey of judgment and exile. YHWH's replenishment is personal and direct: he will fill what exile has emptied. This is covenant renewal as personal revitalization.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>At this I awoke and looked, and my sleep was pleasant to me</strong>. A remarkable autobiographical aside: Jeremiah woke from a vision or dream in which these restoration oracles had been received. <em>My sleep was pleasant to me</em>: the content of the restoration vision produced rest and peace, in contrast to the anguish that pervades most of Jeremiah's prophetic experience (cf. 20:7–18 — the consuming fire, the mockery, the death-wish). The pleasant sleep is itself a sign: the restoration vision brings peace to the prophet who has been consumed by the burden of judgment.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>Behold, the days are coming, declares YHWH, when I will sow the house of Israel and the house of Judah with the seed of man and the seed of beast</strong>. The repopulation promise: the land emptied by war, famine, pestilence, and deportation will be resown — with people and animals. The sowing-image applies the agricultural framework (cf. 1:10 — I pluck up and destroy; I build and plant) to the human and animal population. Just as a field must be resown after it has been cleared, the covenant land will be repopulated through YHWH's sovereign act of restoration.</p>",
"28": "<p><strong>And it shall come to pass that as I have watched over them to pluck up and break down, to overthrow, destroy, and bring harm, so I will watch over them to build and to plant, declares YHWH</strong>. The six-term schema from Jeremiah's call (1:10) is here applied in its full positive and negative dimensions: the same divine vigilance (<em>shaqad</em>, watch over) that executed judgment will now execute restoration. YHWH did not merely permit the plucking-up and tearing-down; he actively watched over it. The same active divine attention will now be applied to the building and planting. The symmetry is exact and deliberate.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>In those days they shall no longer say: The fathers have eaten sour grapes, and the children's teeth are set on edge</strong>. The <em>sour grapes</em> proverb (cf. Ezek 18:2) reflects a popular complaint about intergenerational punishment: we (the current generation) are suffering for what our fathers did. The proverb expresses both a desire to evade personal accountability (it's not our fault) and a genuine theological confusion about how YHWH's judgment works across generations. The restoration era will render this proverb obsolete.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>But everyone shall die for his own iniquity. Each man who eats sour grapes, his teeth shall be set on edge</strong>. The individual accountability principle: in the restored covenant community, each person will bear the consequences of their own sin, not their ancestors'. This does not deny the generational effects of sin (cf. Deut 5:9 — visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children) but establishes that the primary moral structure is individual accountability. The restoration community will be characterized by clearer lines between personal sin and its consequences, enabling genuine moral growth and responsibility.</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>Behold, the days are coming, declares YHWH, when I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel and the house of Judah</strong>. The <strong>New Covenant</strong> (<em>berith chadashah</em>) — the most theologically significant four words in the Book of Consolation and arguably the single most important phrase in Jeremiah. This is the only explicit use of <em>berith chadashah</em> (new covenant) in the entire Hebrew Bible. The New Covenant encompasses both kingdoms (Israel and Judah), signaling the comprehensive reunification that the restoration promises.</p>",
"32": "<p><strong>Not like the covenant that I made with their fathers on the day when I took them by the hand to bring them out of the land of Egypt, my covenant that they broke, though I was their husband, declares YHWH</strong>. The contrast with the Sinai covenant is explicit and structural: the New Covenant will be definitionally different from what YHWH made at Sinai. The Sinai covenant was breakable — and was broken (<em>asher hemah heferhu</em>). The New Covenant will not be breakable in the same way. The <em>though I was their husband</em> (<em>anochi ba'alti bam</em>) maintains the marriage-covenant imagery that runs throughout Jeremiah (cf. 2:2; 3:1–3) — YHWH was Israel's covenant-husband whom she abandoned.</p>",
"33": "<p><strong>For this is the covenant that I will make with the house of Israel after those days, declares YHWH: I will put my law within them, and I will write it on their hearts. And I will be their God, and they shall be my people</strong>. The three defining features of the New Covenant: (1) <em>internalized law</em> — Torah written on hearts rather than stone tablets. The stone tablets of Sinai (Exod 31:18; 34:1–4) were external; the New Covenant Torah is internal, operating from the inside of human consciousness rather than as an external standard to be obeyed. (2) The covenant formula — <em>I will be their God; they shall be my people</em>. (3) Verse 34 (already written) adds universal knowledge and full forgiveness. Hebrews 8:8–12 quotes vv31–34 as the longest OT quotation in the NT, identifying the New Covenant with the covenant inaugurated by Jesus' death (Luke 22:20; 1 Cor 11:25; Heb 9:15).</p>",
"35": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH, who gives the sun for light by day and the fixed order of the moon and the stars for light by night, who stirs up the sea so that its waves roar — YHWH of hosts is his name</strong>. The cosmic permanence of YHWH's ordering power — sun, moon, stars, sea — is invoked as the basis for the permanence of Israel's covenant relationship. The <em>fixed orders</em> (<em>chuqqot</em>) of the celestial bodies are YHWH's own ordinances, built into the structure of creation. The argument of vv35–37 is: as long as these fixed orders remain, Israel's status before YHWH will remain.</p>",
"36": "<p><strong>If this fixed order departs from before me, declares YHWH, then shall the offspring of Israel cease from being a nation before me forever</strong>. The permanence of Israel's national identity before YHWH is as certain as the permanence of the cosmic order. This is not unconditional prosperity but unconditional covenant identity — Israel will always have standing before YHWH as his covenant people. The logic is creation-theology: the God who maintains the fixed orders of creation can be trusted to maintain his covenant commitments with equal reliability.</p>",
"37": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH: If the heavens above can be measured, and the foundations of the earth below can be explored, then I will cast off all the offspring of Israel for all that they have done, declares YHWH</strong>. The second impossibility argument: measuring the heavens and exploring the earth's foundations are humanly impossible tasks. YHWH will cast off Israel only when these impossible tasks are accomplished — which is to say, never. The hyperbole communicates absolute certainty: YHWH's rejection of Israel is as impossible as human measurement of the infinite cosmos. Whatever Israel's sin, the covenant relationship has a permanence built into creation itself.</p>",
"38": "<p><strong>Behold, the days are coming, declares YHWH, when the city shall be rebuilt for YHWH from the Tower of Hananel to the Corner Gate</strong>. The physical rebuilding of Jerusalem is specified with actual topographic references: the Tower of Hananel (northeast of the city, mentioned in Neh 3:1; 12:39; Zech 14:10) to the Corner Gate (northwest, cf. 2 Kgs 14:13; 2 Chr 26:9). The specific geographic coordinates emphasize that this is a promise about a real city in a real place — not merely spiritual restoration but physical reconstruction.</p>",
"39": "<p><strong>And the measuring line shall go out farther, straight to the hill Gareb, and shall then turn to Goah</strong>. The measuring line extends beyond the pre-exile city limits — the restored Jerusalem will be larger than the city that was destroyed. Gareb and Goah are otherwise unknown locations, likely on the western and southern sides of the city. The expanding measurement signals a city that has outgrown its former boundaries, consistent with the <em>multiply, not few</em> promise of v19.</p>",
"40": "<p><strong>The whole valley of the dead bodies and the ashes, and all the fields as far as the brook Kidron, to the corner of the Horse Gate toward the east, shall be sacred to YHWH. It shall not be uprooted or overthrown anymore forever</strong>. The valley of dead bodies (<em>ha'ashpot vehadeshen</em>) — likely the Hinnom Valley (the location of the worst apostasy and the sign-act of chapter 19) — will be made sacred to YHWH rather than defiled by it. The Kidron Valley, the eastern boundary, and the Horse Gate on the east complete the circuit. The final word: <em>it shall not be uprooted or overthrown anymore forever</em> (<em>le'olam</em>). The permanent inviolability of the restored city reverses everything Jeremiah announced in chapters 7–20. The city that will be destroyed will be restored; the restored city will endure.</p>"
},
"32": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 32 is one of the most dramatically ironic passages in the Hebrew Bible: Jeremiah purchases a field while the Babylonian army is besieging Jerusalem, acting as a sign-act of restoration hope precisely when all visible evidence points to national extinction. <strong>The word that came to Jeremiah from YHWH in the tenth year of Zedekiah king of Judah, which was the eighteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar</strong>. The date is 588/587 BC — the final siege of Jerusalem. Nebuchadnezzar began the siege in Zedekiah's ninth year (2 Kgs 25:1) and took the city in his tenth year (Jer 39:1–2). Jeremiah is purchasing real estate during the last months before Jerusalem's fall.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>At that time the army of the king of Babylon was besieging Jerusalem, and Jeremiah the prophet was shut up in the court of the guard that was in the palace of the king of Judah</strong>. The setting is doubly confined: the city is besieged (enclosed by the Babylonian army) and Jeremiah is imprisoned (enclosed in the palace guard-court). The prophet who counseled surrender is under house arrest, the city he prophesied would fall is being besieged. His prophetic word is being fulfilled in real time around him.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>For Zedekiah king of Judah had imprisoned him, saying, Why do you prophesy and say, Thus says YHWH: Behold, I am giving this city into the hand of the king of Babylon, and he shall capture it</strong>. Jeremiah's imprisonment is a direct consequence of his prophetic message. Zedekiah has imprisoned him for the same reason Jehoiakim wanted to kill Uriah (26:20–23): the prophet announced surrender as YHWH's will, which amounted to treason in a time of active resistance. The charge is accurate — Jeremiah did say exactly this.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>Zedekiah king of Judah shall not escape out of the hand of the Chaldeans, but shall surely be given into the hand of the king of Babylon, and shall speak with him face to face and see him eye to eye</strong>. The specific oracle about Zedekiah's personal fate: he will be captured and brought face-to-face with Nebuchadnezzar. This was historically fulfilled — Zedekiah was captured near Jericho, brought to Nebuchadnezzar's headquarters at Riblah, watched his sons executed, was blinded, and taken to Babylon (2 Kgs 25:4–7; Jer 39:4–7). Face-to-face with the king, as Jeremiah predicted.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>And he shall take Zedekiah to Babylon, and there he shall remain until I visit him, declares YHWH. Though you fight against the Chaldeans, you shall not succeed</strong>. The covenant visit (<em>paqad</em>) of YHWH upon Zedekiah in Babylon — a visit for mercy or judgment, the text is deliberately ambiguous. <em>Though you fight against the Chaldeans, you shall not succeed</em>: resistance is futile. The declaration of futility applies to all military options — no strategy, no alliance, no desperate last-stand will change what YHWH has determined.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>Jeremiah said, The word of YHWH came to me: Hanamel the son of Shallum your uncle is going to come to you and say, Buy my field that is at Anathoth, for the right of redemption by purchase is yours</strong>. The divine foreknowledge confirmed: YHWH tells Jeremiah that his cousin Hanamel will come to him with a field-redemption offer. When Hanamel actually arrives (v8), this prediction is Jeremiah's confirmation that the purchase is YHWH's instruction, not mere family obligation. The anticipation of the visit functions as a prophetic sign: the one who can predict family visits can be trusted with promises about the nation's future.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>Then Hanamel my cousin came to me in the court of the guard, in accordance with the word of YHWH, and said to me, Buy my field that is at Anathoth in the land of Benjamin, for the right of possession and redemption is yours; buy it for yourself</strong>. Hanamel's arrival precisely as predicted confirms that the subsequent field purchase is a divinely commanded sign-act, not merely family business. The <em>right of redemption</em> (<em>mishpat hage'ulah</em>) is the kinsman-redeemer provision of Leviticus 25:25: when a clan member is forced to sell his land, the nearest kin has the right (and obligation) to buy it and keep it within the family. Jeremiah is the appropriate redeemer for Hanamel's distressed property.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>Then I knew that this was the word of YHWH</strong>. The confirmatory function of the prediction: Hanamel's arrival validates the divine origin of the purchase command. The prophet who was uncertain whether to comply with an apparently bizarre instruction (buy land during a siege?) finds in the fulfilled prediction the confirmation he needed. This is an important insight into how prophetic guidance worked in practice: confirmation through fulfilled prior knowledge.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>And I bought the field at Anathoth from Hanamel my cousin, and weighed out the money to him, seventeen shekels of silver</strong>. The actual transaction: seventeen shekels of silver for the Anathoth field. This is a real price for a real property transaction — archaeologists have found ancient Near Eastern field sale contracts with comparable amounts. The specific price details authenticate the historicity of the transaction. Jeremiah pays from whatever resources he has while imprisoned, investing in property in a city about to fall to an enemy who will level it.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>I signed the deed, sealed it, got witnesses, and weighed the money on scales</strong>. The legal procedure is scrupulous: signature, sealing, witnesses, and weighed silver. This is authentic ancient Near Eastern real estate protocol. The meticulous legal formality in the midst of siege and imprisonment makes the transaction even more remarkable — Jeremiah is performing the full legal requirements for a valid property transfer as if future enforcement of the deed were fully expected.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>Then I took the sealed deed of purchase, containing the terms and conditions and the open copy</strong>. Ancient Near Eastern property deeds were typically written in two copies on a single clay tablet: the sealed copy (protected against tampering) and an open copy (accessible for reference). The sealed copy would be stored in a clay jar; the open copy could be consulted when needed. This dual-copy system provided both security and accessibility — Jeremiah is following established legal practice.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>And I gave the deed of purchase to Baruch the son of Neriah son of Mahseiah, in the presence of Hanamel my cousin, in the presence of the witnesses who signed the deed of purchase, and in the presence of all the Judeans who were sitting in the court of the guard</strong>. Baruch ben Neriah is Jeremiah's scribe and primary disciple — the one who wrote down Jeremiah's oracles (36:4), read them in the Temple (36:6–10), and eventually compiled/edited the book of Jeremiah. His custody of the deed of purchase places the most important sign-act in Jeremiah's ministry in the hands of the man who will preserve Jeremiah's entire prophetic legacy.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>And I charged Baruch in their presence, saying</strong>. Jeremiah delivers specific instructions to Baruch regarding the deed's preservation — the instructions that follow explain the purpose of the entire sign-act.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH of hosts, the God of Israel: Take these deeds, both this sealed deed of purchase and this open deed, and put them in an earthenware vessel, that they may last for a long time</strong>. Clay jars preserve documents extremely well — the Dead Sea Scrolls, preserved in ceramic jars for 2,000 years, demonstrate the effectiveness of this archival method. The instruction to preserve the deed for a long time is itself the theological point: the deed will need to be kept long enough for conditions to change, for the siege to end, for Babylon to fall, for exiles to return and claim their ancestral properties. The jar-preservation anticipates a long wait.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>For thus says YHWH of hosts, the God of Israel: Houses and fields and vineyards shall again be bought in this land</strong>. The theological explanation of the entire sign-act, delivered in the most economically absurd possible moment. While the city is besieged, its houses being reduced to rubble, its fields lying fallow, YHWH declares: normal economic life will return. Fields will be bought and sold. The deed Jeremiah is filing away in a clay jar represents a future transaction that the current generation may not live to see but that YHWH guarantees will happen.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>After I had given the deed of purchase to Baruch the son of Neriah, I prayed to YHWH, saying</strong>. Jeremiah's prayer follows the sign-act — a pattern of action then theological reflection. The prayer (vv16–25) is remarkable for its honest tension: it begins with confident doxology and ends with a question that essentially asks, <em>why did you tell me to do this?</em></p>",
"17": "<p><strong>Ah, Lord YHWH! It is you who have made the heavens and the earth by your great power and by your outstretched arm. Nothing is too hard for you</strong>. The prayer opens with creation theology: YHWH made heaven and earth by his <em>great power and outstretched arm</em> — the Exodus-warfare language applied to creation. <em>Nothing is too hard for you</em> (<em>lo-yippale' mimkha kol-davar</em>): the theological affirmation that grounds all petition. The God who created the cosmos can restore a devastated nation — the restoration promise is not beyond his power.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>You show steadfast love to thousands, but you repay the guilt of fathers to their children after them, O great and mighty God, whose name is YHWH of hosts</strong>. The Exodus doxology of Exodus 34:6–7 echoes here: YHWH showing <em>chesed</em> to thousands while visiting iniquity on the third and fourth generation. Jeremiah has lived through the fulfillment of both aspects: he has seen the steadfast love of YHWH's covenant promises and the visiting of the fathers' guilt in the exile of his own generation. Both are real; both are YHWH's.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>Great in counsel and mighty in deed, whose eyes are open to all the ways of the children of man, rewarding each one according to his ways and according to the fruit of his deeds</strong>. The divine omniscience and moral recompense formula: YHWH sees every human way and action, and his reward/punishment is calibrated accordingly (<em>according to his ways and the fruit of his deeds</em>). This is the covenant framework applied at the cosmic level: the God who judges nations by this standard is also the God who restores nations by his free grace.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>Who performed signs and wonders in the land of Egypt, and to this day in Israel and among all mankind, and have made a name for yourself, as at this day</strong>. The Exodus signs and wonders (<em>otot umoftim</em>) as the paradigm of divine intervention in history. <em>To this day</em>: the Exodus events were not ancient history but living memory, the continuing basis of Israel's identity and YHWH's ongoing reputation among the nations. The God whose name was made great in Egypt is the same God who can make his name great through Israel's restoration from Babylon.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>You brought your people Israel out of the land of Egypt with signs and wonders, with a strong hand and outstretched arm, and with great terror</strong>. The Exodus vocabulary accumulates: signs and wonders, strong hand, outstretched arm, great terror (<em>mora gadol</em>). This is the Deuteronomic confession (Deut 26:8) quoted almost verbatim. Jeremiah is embedding his prayer in Israel's founding narrative — the same God who did all this in Egypt is the one being addressed now.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>And you gave them this land, which you swore to their fathers to give them, a land flowing with milk and honey</strong>. The Patriarchal promise and its Exodus-era fulfillment: the land oath sworn to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob (Gen 15:18–21; 28:13–15) was executed in the Conquest. The land given is now being taken away in exile — but the original gift was a covenant act of YHWH, and the exile does not cancel the covenant. The land-gift grounds the hope of restoration.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>And they entered and took possession of it. But they did not obey your voice or walk in your law. They did nothing of all you commanded them to do. Therefore you have made all this disaster come upon them</strong>. The audit of covenant history from possession through violation to disaster: receive, disobey, suffer. The logic is consistent and transparent. Jeremiah's prayer does not suppress the covenant accounting — it faces it directly. The disaster is YHWH's just response to covenant violation; acknowledging this is essential to genuine prayer.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>Behold, the siege mounds have come up to the city to take it, and the city is given into the hands of the Chaldeans who are fighting against it, because of sword and famine and pestilence. What you spoke has come to pass, and behold, you see it</strong>. The present visible reality: the siege works are in place, the city is falling, the judgment triad is active. <em>What you spoke has come to pass</em>: the prophetic word has been fulfilled. Jeremiah is noting that YHWH's announcements have proven accurate — which is both a confirmation of prophetic authority and a preparation for the question that follows.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>Yet you, O Lord YHWH, have said to me, Buy the field for money and get witnesses — though the city is given into the hands of the Chaldeans</strong>. The honest tension of the prayer surfaces: the same YHWH who announced the city's fall has commanded Jeremiah to buy a field in the falling city. The contradiction is real and admitted. Jeremiah is not pretending to understand YHWH's logic; he is pressing the apparent incoherence back to the one who created it. This is the prayer of authentic faith: confessing incomprehension while maintaining trust.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>The word of YHWH came to Jeremiah: Behold, I am YHWH, the God of all flesh. Is anything too hard for me?</strong> YHWH's response begins with a question that echoes and completes Jeremiah's own affirmation (<em>nothing is too hard for you</em>, v17). The title <em>God of all flesh</em> (<em>Elohei kol-basar</em>): YHWH's domain is every living creature — he is not limited to Israel, to the covenant land, or to the Temple. <em>Is anything too hard for me?</em> — the rhetorical question that frames everything that follows. The field purchase in a besieged city seems impossible as a meaningful investment; YHWH asserts his power over every apparent impossibility.</p>",
"27": "<p>YHWH's self-identification as <em>God of all flesh</em> establishes the scope of his authority. The restoration of a nation, the rebuilding of a city, the return of exiles from across the known world — all of these fall within the domain of the God who governs all living things. The question <em>is anything too hard for me?</em> is not rhetorical posturing but a direct invitation to trust: bring your hardest cases and watch what I can do.</p>",
"28": "<p><strong>Therefore, thus says YHWH: Behold, I am giving this city into the hands of the Chaldeans and into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, and he shall capture it</strong>. YHWH's answer to Jeremiah's prayer-question begins with the judgment: yes, the city will fall. The affirmation of Jeremiah's prophetic announcement about Jerusalem's fall (the same announcement that got him imprisoned) comes directly from YHWH. There is no miraculous reversal at the last moment. The judgment is real, coming, and irreversible.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>The Chaldeans who are fighting against this city shall come and set this city on fire and burn it, with the houses on whose rooftops offerings have been made to Baal and drink offerings have been poured out to other gods, to provoke me to anger</strong>. The burning is specified, and the reason is given: the rooftop altars to Baal and other gods (cf. 19:13) that covered Jerusalem's residential architecture. The city is burned not by Babylonian capriciousness but as the direct result of the apostasy that the houses themselves witnessed and hosted.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>For the children of Israel and the children of Judah have done nothing but evil in my sight from their youth. The children of Israel have done nothing but provoke me to anger by the work of their hands, declares YHWH</strong>. The comprehensive audit: from their youth (<em>mina'ureihem</em>) — from the beginning of the nation's existence — both Israel and Judah have engaged in covenant violation. The <em>work of their hands</em> (idols) is the consistent trigger of divine anger throughout the book. The judgment is not a recent decision but the culmination of a long accumulation.</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>This city has aroused my anger and wrath, from the day it was built to this day, so that I will remove it from my sight</strong>. The city of Jerusalem itself — from its Davidic founding — has been a source of covenant failure rather than covenant faithfulness. The Temple that was supposed to be the place of divine presence and covenant maintenance became the location of covenant violation. <em>Remove it from my sight</em>: the departure of the divine presence from Jerusalem, which Ezekiel sees in his vision (Ezek 10–11), is the inner meaning of the city's fall.</p>",
"32": "<p><strong>Because of all the evil of the children of Israel and the children of Judah that they did to provoke me to anger — their kings, their officials, their priests, their prophets, the men of Judah, and the inhabitants of Jerusalem</strong>. The comprehensive social indictment: every stratum of society (kings, officials, priests, prophets, general population) bears responsibility for the covenant failure. No group is exempt; the judgment falls on the entire social hierarchy that was supposed to maintain covenant fidelity but instead led covenant violation.</p>",
"33": "<p><strong>They have turned their back to me and not their face. And though I have taught them persistently, they have not listened to receive instruction</strong>. The back-versus-face image (cf. 2:27; 18:17): the people have turned away from YHWH in posture and in orientation. The teaching (<em>hashem veshalloach</em>, rising early and sending) has been persistent and urgent; the listening has been absent. The same formula as 7:13, 25:3–4 — the exhaustion of the channels of covenant communication.</p>",
"34": "<p><strong>They set up their abominations in the house that is called by my name, to defile it</strong>. The Temple desecration — the installation of foreign cult objects within the Temple precincts (cf. 2 Kgs 21:4–7; Ezek 8) — is the culminating covenant violation. The house <em>called by my name</em> (<em>asher niqra shemi alav</em>): the divine name-claim on the Temple makes its desecration the most direct form of covenant insult. The abominations within YHWH's own house are the final provocation.</p>",
"35": "<p><strong>They built the high places of Baal in the Valley of the Son of Hinnom, to offer up their sons and daughters to Molech, though I did not command them, nor did it enter into my mind, that they should do this abomination</strong>. The Hinnom Valley / Topheth child sacrifice (cf. chapter 19) is again specified as the theological nadir — the crime YHWH most explicitly disclaims (<em>did not command, nor did it enter my mind</em>). The triple denial that appeared in 19:5 recurs here, emphasizing the absolute incompatibility of child sacrifice with Yahwistic covenant religion.</p>",
"36": "<p><strong>Now therefore thus says YHWH, the God of Israel, concerning this city of which you say, It is given into the hand of the king of Babylon by sword, by famine, and by pestilence</strong>. The pivot from judgment to restoration: <em>now therefore</em> introduces the second part of YHWH's response to Jeremiah's prayer. The judgment having been fully confirmed, the restoration can now be announced. The same city that is being destroyed will be the city of restoration.</p>",
"37": "<p><strong>Behold, I will gather them from all the countries to which I drove them in my anger and my wrath and in great indignation. I will bring them back to this place, and I will make them dwell in safety</strong>. The gathering from all countries — the comprehensive diaspora ingathering (cf. 29:14; 31:8) — is YHWH's act of reversing his own judgment. <em>In my anger, my wrath, and in great indignation</em>: the exile was fully YHWH's act; the restoration is equally fully YHWH's act. <em>Dwell in safety</em>: the security that the covenant community in Jeremiah's time had lost — from foreign invasion and internal social breakdown — will be restored.</p>",
"38": "<p><strong>And they shall be my people, and I will be their God</strong>. The covenant formula at the heart of the entire Book of Consolation. The sixth time this formula appears in Jeremiah (7:23; 11:4; 24:7; 30:22; 31:1, 33; 32:38) — each occurrence marking a stage in the covenant-judgment-restoration arc. Here it is the anchor of the restoration promise: the relationship that was strained to the breaking point by exile is fully reconstituted.</p>",
"39": "<p><strong>I will give them one heart and one way, that they fear me forever, for their own good and the good of their children after them</strong>. The <em>one heart</em> (<em>lev echad</em>) is the undivided heart of covenant fidelity — the opposite of the divided heart that pursued both YHWH and idols. This is the New Covenant promise of 31:33 (internalized Torah) expressed in different vocabulary: a heart that is unified in its orientation toward YHWH. <em>One way</em> (<em>derek echad</em>): the single covenant path rather than the many wandering paths of apostasy (cf. 6:16 — the ancient paths).</p>",
"40": "<p><strong>I will make with them an everlasting covenant, that I will not turn away from doing good to them. And I will put the fear of me in their hearts, that they may not turn from me</strong>. The <em>everlasting covenant</em> (<em>berith olam</em>) is the New Covenant of 31:31–34 described with permanence language: YHWH commits never to turn away from doing good. The internal covenant-keeping (<em>the fear of me in their hearts</em>) addresses the root failure of the Sinai covenant: the people kept turning from YHWH because their hearts were not secured to him. The New Covenant secures the heart from the inside.</p>",
"41": "<p><strong>I will rejoice in doing them good, and I will plant them in this land in faithfulness, with all my heart and all my soul</strong>. <em>With all my heart and all my soul</em> (<em>bechol-libbi uvechol-nafshi</em>): the covenant formula of Deuteronomy 6:5 (love YHWH with all your heart and soul) is applied to YHWH's own commitment to Israel. The God who commanded Israel to love him wholeheartedly will himself love Israel wholeheartedly in the restoration. The restoration is not a reluctant act of divine obligation but a joyful expression of divine love.</p>",
"42": "<p><strong>For thus says YHWH: Just as I have brought all this great disaster upon this people, so I will bring upon them all the good that I promise them</strong>. The symmetry of YHWH's covenant administration: the same certainty that characterized the disaster will characterize the restoration. The judgment was not exaggerated; neither is the promise. The people who watched the siege works rise around their city can be equally certain that the restoration promises will be executed with equal thoroughness.</p>",
"43": "<p><strong>Fields shall be bought in this land of which you are saying, It is a desolation, without man or beast; it is given into the hand of the Chaldeans</strong>. The direct connection to the sign-act: the fields-will-be-bought promise (v15) is here expanded into the full restoration context. The field Jeremiah purchased is not merely a personal investment but a prophetic deposit — the first transaction in a future market of covenant-land activity that YHWH guarantees will flourish.</p>",
"44": "<p><strong>Fields shall be bought for money, and deeds shall be signed and sealed and witnessed, in the land of Benjamin, in the places around Jerusalem, and in the cities of Judah, in the cities of the hill country, in the cities of the Shephelah, and in the cities of the Negeb; for I will restore their fortunes, declares YHWH</strong>. The geographic completeness of the restoration: Benjamin (where Anathoth is), Jerusalem's surroundings, the cities of Judah, the hill country, the Shephelah (coastal lowlands), the Negeb (southern desert fringe). Every region of the covenant land will be restored to normal economic activity — property transactions, legal deeds, witnesses. The meticulous legal procedure Jeremiah performed in a prison courtyard (vv9–12) will become the ordinary practice of a restored community throughout every corner of the land.</p>"
}
}

